<doc id="4729" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=4729" title="Chubu International Airport opens">
<h1>Chubu International Airport opens</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Chubu%20International%20Airport%20opens&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

Nagoya – 

Chubu International Airport, &lt;a href="w%3AJapan"&gt;Japan&lt;/a&gt;'s third major international gateway, has opened near &lt;a href="w%3ANagoya"&gt;Nagoya&lt;/a&gt;. Also known as Centrair, the 24-hour airport is on an artificial island 30 minutes south from the center of town and opens on time to serve &lt;a href="w%3AExpo%202005"&gt;Expo 2005&lt;/a&gt;, kicking off in March. The new airport replaces the existing Nagoya airport and also takes over its IATA code NGO.

