<doc id="5454" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=5454" title="Nobel Laureate Hans Bethe passes away at age of 98">
<h1>Nobel Laureate Hans Bethe passes away at age of 98</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Nobel%20Laureate%20Hans%20Bethe%20passes%20away%20at%20age%20of%2098&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

&lt;a href="Nobel%20Prize"&gt;Nobel Laureate in Physics&lt;/a&gt; ♡❤♡&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AHans%20Bethe"&gt;Hans Bethe&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; ♡❤♡ died in his home in &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AIthaca%2C%20New%20York"&gt;Ithaca, New York&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; on March 6, 2005, according to &lt;a href="Cornell%20University"&gt;Cornell University&lt;/a&gt;, where he was professor emeritus of &lt;a href="physics"&gt;physics&lt;/a&gt;. 

Hans Albrecht Bethe (pronounced ♡❤Bay-ta♡❤) was born on July 2, 1906 in the city of &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AStrasbourg"&gt;Strasbourg&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , then part of &lt;a href="Germany"&gt;Germany&lt;/a&gt; (now part of &lt;a href="France"&gt;France&lt;/a&gt;). He studied physics at &lt;a href="Frankfurt"&gt;Frankfurt&lt;/a&gt; and obtained his doctorate from the &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AUniversity%20of%20Munich"&gt;University of Munich&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; . 

Bethe, whose mother was [[Judaism|Jewish}}, fled Germany in 1933 when the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Nazi Party|Nazi Party]]&lt;/span&gt; came to power. Bethe, along with hundreds of other Jewish academics, were fired from their posts as a result of one of [[Adolf Hitler]]'s first anti-Semitic acts. Bethe moved first to [[England]] and in 1935 to the [[USA]] where he taught at Cornell University. 

Between 1935 and 1938, he studied [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:nuclear reaction|nuclear reactions]]&lt;/span&gt; and reaction cross sections. This research was useful to Bethe in more quantitatively developing [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Niels Bohr|Niels Bohr]]&lt;/span&gt; 's theory of the compound nucleus.

During [[World War II]], he served as a prominent member of a special summer session at the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:University of California, Berkeley|University of California, Berkeley]]&lt;/span&gt; at the invitation of [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Robert Oppenheimer|Robert Oppenheimer]]&lt;/span&gt; , which outlined the first designs for the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:atomic bomb|atomic bomb]]&lt;/span&gt; and served as the beginning of the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Manhattan Project|Manhattan Project]]&lt;/span&gt; . When Oppenheimer started the secret weapons design laboratory, [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Los Alamos National Laboratory|Los Alamos]]&lt;/span&gt; , he appointed Bethe as Director of the Theoretical Division. 

After the war, Bethe argued that a crash project for the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:hydrogen bomb|hydrogen bomb]]&lt;/span&gt; should not be attempted, though after [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Harry S. Truman|President Truman]]&lt;/span&gt; announced the beginning of such a crash project, and the outbreak of the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Korean War|Korean War]]&lt;/span&gt; , he signed up and played a key role in the weapon's development. In 1968, he reflected upon the choice, noting that "It seemed quite logical. But sometimes I wish I were more consistent an idealist." Though he would see the project through to its end, in Bethe's account he was primarily hopeful that the weapon would be impossible to produce. He later characterized [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Stanislaw Ulam|Stanislaw Ulam]]&lt;/span&gt; as the "father" of the hydrogen bomb, and [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Edward Teller|Edward Teller]]&lt;/span&gt; as its "mother," and himself as its "midwife." 

Among his many honors, Bethe received the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Max Planck medal|Max Planck medal]]&lt;/span&gt; in 1955, and in 1961 he was awarded the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Eddington Medal|Eddington Medal]]&lt;/span&gt; of the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:Royal Astronomical Society|Royal Astronomical Society]]&lt;/span&gt; for his work in identifying the energy generating processes in stars. In 1967, Bethe was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for his studies of the production of solar and stellar energy, [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:stellar nucleosynthesis|stellar nucleosynthesis]]&lt;/span&gt; . He postulated that the source of this energy are [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:nuclear fusion|thermonuclear reactions]]&lt;/span&gt; in which [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:hydrogen|hydrogen]]&lt;/span&gt; was converted into [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:helium|helium]]&lt;/span&gt; .

During the 1980s and 1990s, Bethe campaigned for the peaceful use of [[nuclear energy]], arguing against the [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:nuclear arms ace|nuclear arms ace]]&lt;/span&gt; and against [[Category:Pages with defaulting non-local links]]&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;[[w:nuclear testing|nuclear testing]]&lt;/span&gt; . In 1995, at the age of 88, Bethe wrote an open letter calling on all scientists to "cease and desist" from working on any aspect of nuclear weapons development and manufacture. In 2004, he signed a letter along with 47 other Nobel laureates endorsing [[John Kerry]] for president of the United States citing [[George W. Bush|Bush]]'s apparent misuse of science.

&lt;br style="clear:none;"&gt;
&lt;center&gt;
&lt;/center&gt; 
<h2>Sources</h2>
